<!-- post # 1 --><font color="#FF0000">POST WAR GENERATION</font><br><tt>Sun Nov 17 17:17:50 US/Eastern 1996</tt><p>I am 30 years old and after viewing this website I must consider myself part of the Post War Generation. Though I did not have any immediate family members such as my father who served in Vietnam, there were those men my father befriended during his '61-'65 Navy enlistment who did serve there. This fact however was not known to him until several years ago. My father's enlistment came up in 1965 and after saying farewell to the Naval 53rd Construction Battalion he lost touch with them. Many years later he ran into an old buddy who informed him that the battalion received orders for Vietnam shortly after my father's departure and that half the battalion made it out. At that point, my father did not wish to hear who made it and who didnt. As he told me this story a few years ago, he found it difficult to talk about. And now, I find it difficult to think about, to imagine what it must be like to lose your friends in war at such a young age. What it has made me consider is what such deaths mean for my generation, many lives of absent fathers and mothers, many lives of silence about our parents service in Vietnam, many years of ignorance about what it means to live and die in war and to live with the consequences in peacetime. And I think about the times that will not come to pass when my father would have introduced me to his buddies as his &quot;oldest boy&quot; with a measure of pride. And I also consider what kind of pain so many men and women have kept hidden from us, their children, grandchildren, nephews &amp; nieces, those children who now come of age, have witnessed the Panama invasion, the Persian Gulf War, vote, have families, visit the Wall, who wonder how to heal the wounds in their parents lives. For the last few years I have wondered whether my generation wants to hear what happened in Vietnam, whether enough people are talking about it in order to counteract the aura of shame surrounding the Vietnam War and its participants and victims as portrayed by our government (in reference to the idea that the Persian Gulf War somehow redeemed our military might from dishonor after Vietnam, and to the idea that the lessons of Vietnam were now &quot;learned&quot; as seen in the conduct of the Persian Gulf War). As I have begun developing a personal interest in the history of America's military ventures in this century, I realize the importance of speaking about Vietnam by those who were there to those of us who may one day survive our own &quot;Vietnam&quot;. And I have come away with this conviction, that the shame over Vietnam must be put away, not only in terms of our government's conduct of the war but in terms of each soldier's personal conduct, those actions that were elicited from them during a time of great stress, confusion, survival, bonding, and pain. And I beg of you who served in the war, please talk with us, your children and grandchildren, share with us that part of your lives that never leaves you, allow your stories to guide us as nothing else ever will toward a more humane and informed citizenship and community in the world. As part of the Post War Generation, we are in this together.<p><code>-- Peregrinn@aol.com  (Joel Hernandez) </code><p>